         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this jewel ... merits ... 1. Knowing also the object ... the Ocean's </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Bhūta [monsters] (went?) to the Bodhisattva ... (the Bodhisattva says:) In [the tune] ṣeraśi-niṣkramānt: "Previously through ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [1a] Through very horrible, high</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">..., through big ... brought me the jewel; through huge efforts, all the Bhūta [monsters]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">also desiring [it], (took away) this cintāmaṇi [jewel]. [1c] ... Gather and bring jewels in excellent [and] pure </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">ārtänts! [1d] Beyond this do not de(sire) this jewel! ... Even if at [the] (present) time you desire this one, it is I that nevertheless</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6 #b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Ich jedenfalls werde dieses Juwel jetzt selbst suchen.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">I at least will now search for this jewel myself.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>149-50</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">desire this jewel myself now. Thereupon ... comparable to the summit of the mountain (without) trembling [and] without shaking</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the excellent, powerful, strong (Bodhisattva?) ... the excellent meditation not shared with the ... Pratyekabuddhas</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">desirous (to appear in the world) [and] (to make) [it] manifest, having gathered [his] garment close [about] </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[his] loins and ... having taken the shell of a turtle, with one foot</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">he descended to the top of the mountain Cakravaḍā. ... having (de)scended he stood ready to pour out </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the whole water from the Ocean. Thereupon the (Bhūta [monsters] of the) Ocean ... because of not under(standing) the excellent capacity (of the Bodhisattva) [and] not showing re(morse) ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">Both fragments were joined by Siegling in his personal copy, where he further noted on p. 26: "den von den Meer-Wesen gestohlenen Cintāmaṇi erhält der Bodhisattva zurück, da er das Meer auszuschöpfen droht mit seiner Schildkrötenschale." (The Boddhisattva receives back the Cintāmaṇi that has been stolen by the sea creatures after threatening to scoop out the sea with his turtle shell bowl.)</note><note type="remarks">Number 121 is written on the margin of the verso side, but the number 110 (sic!) inside the string hole, the latter by a different hand in careless script. Note that deviating numbering between margin and string hole is also attested for the series <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a15"/> to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a24"/> which belongs to the same manuscript. There the difference is likewise between nine and ten numbers, the string-hole number being the lesser one.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">About 10 akṣaras are missing between the fragments. Siegling's proposal in his personal copy of <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1921"/></bibl> <hi>pe(nu ca)m</hi> is impossible since <hi>nu</hi> is not an option; fremdzeichen <hi rend="underline">m</hi> is possible but uncertain.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">About 10 to 12 akṣaras are missing between the fragments. The tune has 4x25 syllables (5/5/8/7).</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">The dot at the end of the line interrupts a sentence; rather, it is a number one that has been misplaced during copying, since it is missing after pāda 1d.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="lingcomment">The reading <hi>ṅkatsi</hi> is certain; accordingly, the form can only be an infinitive of a verb with present III or IV. Such a verb is as yet unattested in TA, but it could be the first attestation of the TA equivalent of TB <hi>präṅk<hi rend="superscript">(ā)</hi></hi>- 'to restrain' or <hi>tsäṅk<hi rend="superscript">(ā)</hi></hi>- 'to arise', more likely the latter.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">The ligatura ‹yma› with a second ‹u› is peculiar; it hardly represents <hi>y<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>mā</hi>; rather it is a misspelling for <hi>yāmlune</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
