               <item n="m_philcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;Both fragments were joined by Siegling in his personal copy, where he further noted on p. 26: "den von den Meer-Wesen gestohlenen Cintāmaṇi erhält der Bodhisattva zurück, da er das Meer auszuschöpfen droht mit seiner Schildkrötenschale." (The Boddhisattva receives back the Cintāmaṇi that has been stolen by the sea creatures after threatening to scoop out the sea with his turtle shell bowl.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a1.&lt;/b&gt; About 10 akṣaras are missing between the fragments. Siegling's proposal in his personal copy of [[TochSprR(A)]] &lt;i&gt;pe(nu ca)m&lt;/i&gt; is impossible since &lt;i&gt;nu&lt;/i&gt; is not an option; fremdzeichen &lt;u&gt;m&lt;/u&gt; is possible but uncertain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a2.&lt;/b&gt; About 10 to 12 akṣaras are missing between the fragments. The tune has 4x25 syllables (5/5/8/7).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a6.&lt;/b&gt; The dot at the end of the line interrupts a sentence; rather, it is a number one that has been misplaced during copying, since it is missing after pāda 1d.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b6.&lt;/b&gt; The ligatura ‹yma› with a second ‹u› is peculiar; it hardly represents &lt;i&gt;y&lt;sub&gt;u&lt;/sub&gt;mā&lt;/i&gt;; rather it is a misspelling for &lt;i&gt;yāmlune&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
